  "What is a 'distribution-free test'?": "",
  "A test that only works with the normal distribution": "",
  "Another name for nonparametric tests, because they do not require specific distributional assumptions": "",
  "A test that has no power": "",
  "A test that ignores all data structure": "",
  "Nonparametric tests are called 'distribution-free' because they do not assume the data come from any particular probability distribution family.": "",
  "What is the 'sign test'?": "",
  "A test for correlation between variables": "",
  "A parametric test requiring normally distributed data": "",
  "A test that uses all data values and their magnitudes": "",
  "A simple nonparametric test that considers only the signs (+ or -) of differences, ignoring magnitudes": "",
  "The sign test uses only the direction of differences (positive or negative), not their magnitude. It is one of the simplest nonparametric tests and is very robust but less powerful than the Wilcoxon signed-rank test.": "",
  "What does 'statistical power' mean?": "",
  "The strength of the effect being studied": "",
  "The probability of a Type I error": "",
  "The sample size needed for a study": "",
  "The probability of correctly rejecting a false null hypothesis": "",
  "Statistical power = 1 - P(Type II error). It is the probability of detecting a true effect when one exists. Higher power means a better chance of finding real differences.": "",
  "What does 'bootstrapping' mean in statistics?": "",
  "A method that requires normality assumptions": "",
  "Using theoretical distributions to compute p-values": "",
  "A resampling method that draws repeated samples with replacement from observed data to estimate the sampling distribution": "",
  "The same procedure as the t-test": "",
  "Bootstrapping is a modern nonparametric approach that builds an empirical sampling distribution by repeatedly resampling from the observed data with replacement, requiring no distributional assumptions.": "",
  "What is the 'asymptotic relative efficiency' of a nonparametric test?": "",
  "A ratio comparing the sample size needed by a nonparametric test to achieve the same power as its parametric counterpart": "",
  "It is always 100%, meaning nonparametric and parametric tests have identical power for every sample": "",
  "A measure of how fast the p-value approaches zero as the sample size increases in the given analysis": "",
  "The speed at which the test runs on a computer, measuring computational efficiency of the algorithm": "",
  "Asymptotic relative efficiency compares nonparametric to parametric tests. For example, the Mann-Whitney test has about 95.5% efficiency relative to the t-test under normality, meaning it needs only slightly more data to achieve the same power.": "",
  "What does 'ordinal data' mean?": "",
  "Data collected in chronological order": "",
  "Data that can be ranked in order but the differences between ranks are not necessarily equal": "",
  "Data with exact numerical values and equal intervals": "",
  "Data that is always normally distributed": "",
  "Ordinal data has a natural order (e.g., pain ratings: mild, moderate, severe) but the intervals between categories are not necessarily equal. Nonparametric tests are ideal for ordinal data.": "",
  "What is the 'Wilcoxon Rank-Sum Test'?": "",
  "A parametric test for paired data": "",
  "Equivalent to the Mann-Whitney U Test; it compares two independent groups using ranks": "",
  "A test for comparing three or more groups": "",
  "Another name for the Wilcoxon Signed-Rank Test": "",
  "The Wilcoxon Rank-Sum Test and the Mann-Whitney U Test are mathematically equivalent tests for comparing two independent groups using ranked data.": "",
  "What does 'robust to outliers' mean?": "",
  "The test's results are not heavily influenced by extreme values": "",
  "The test removes all outliers before analysis": "",
  "The test requires outliers to function correctly": "",
  "The test is only valid when there are no outliers": "",
  "Nonparametric tests are robust to outliers because they use ranks rather than raw values. An extreme outlier gets the highest or lowest rank, but its extreme magnitude does not disproportionately affect the test statistic.": "",
  "What does 'permutation test' refer to?": "",
  "A parametric test based on the normal distribution": "",
  "A method for computing Pearson's correlation": "",
  "A nonparametric test that calculates the test statistic for all possible rearrangements of the data to build a reference distribution": "",
  "A test that only works with categorical data": "",
  "Permutation tests shuffle group labels among all observations to generate the null distribution, then compare the observed statistic to this distribution. No distributional assumptions are needed.": "",
  "What is the key advantage of Spearman's r_s over Pearson's r?": "",
  "Spearman's r_s measures causation while Pearson's r does not": "",
  "Spearman's r_s is always larger than Pearson's r": "",
  "Spearman's r_s detects any monotonic relationship and does not require linearity or normality": "",
  "Spearman's r_s only works with large samples": "",
  "Spearman's r_s ranks both variables and computes the Pearson correlation on the ranks. This captures monotonic (not just linear) relationships and is resistant to outliers and non-normality.": "",
  "A physical therapist rates patient pain on a scale of 1-10 before and after treatment for 15 patients. The differences are not normally distributed. Which test should she use to determine if treatment reduces pain?": "",
  "Independent-samples t-test": "",
  "Wilcoxon Signed-Rank Test": "",
  "The data are paired (before/after for the same patients), the pain scale is ordinal, and the differences are not normal. The Wilcoxon Signed-Rank Test is the appropriate nonparametric alternative to the paired t-test.": "",
  "A marketing team wants to compare customer satisfaction ratings (on a 5-point Likert scale) between online and in-store shoppers. The data are ordinal and the distributions are highly skewed. With 25 online and 30 in-store shoppers, which test is most appropriate?": "",
  "Mann-Whitney U Test": "",
  "Two independent groups, ordinal data, and non-normal distributions all point to the Mann-Whitney U Test as the appropriate choice.": "",
  "A food scientist ranks the taste quality of bread made with four different flour types. Each of 10 panelists rates all four types. The data are ordinal and the panelists rate all conditions. Which test should be used?": "",
  "Friedman test": "",
  "Chi-square test of independence": "",
  "Kruskal-Wallis test": "",
  "This is a repeated-measures design (each panelist rates all four flour types) with ordinal data. The Friedman test is the nonparametric alternative to repeated-measures ANOVA.": "",
  "A researcher measures income (in dollars) for three education groups (high school, bachelor's, graduate). Income distributions are heavily right-skewed with outliers. Each group has about 20 participants. Which test should the researcher use?": "",
  "Three independent groups with heavily skewed data and outliers call for the Kruskal-Wallis test, which is the nonparametric alternative to one-way ANOVA and is robust to non-normality.": "",
  "A biologist studies the relationship between tree age (years) and trunk diameter (cm) for 30 trees. Both variables are measured but the relationship appears curved (monotonic but not linear). Which correlation measure is better?": "",
  "Pearson's r, because it handles any relationship": "",
  "Spearman's r_s, because it measures monotonic relationships without requiring linearity": "",
  "Chi-square, because the data are continuous": "",
  "Neither correlation applies to biological data": "",
  "Spearman's r_s captures monotonic relationships regardless of whether the relationship is linear. Since tree age and diameter increase together but not at a constant rate, Spearman's r_s is more appropriate than Pearson's r.": "",
  "A researcher has 8 patients' blood pressure readings before and after a new medication. The sample is too small to verify normality. She uses the sign test and finds 7 out of 8 patients had lower blood pressure after treatment. Under H-null (no effect), what is the probability of 7 or more successes out of 8?": "",
  "0.500": "",
  "0.125": "",
  "0.035": "",
  "0.875": "",
  "Under H-null, each difference is equally likely to be + or - (p = 0.5). P(X >= 7) = P(X=7) + P(X=8) = C(8,7)(0.5)^8 + C(8,8)(0.5)^8 = (8 + 1)/256 = 9/256 = 0.035.": "",
  "A sports analyst uses bootstrapping to estimate the 95% confidence interval for the median marathon finish time from a sample of 50 runners. He resamples 10,000 times. What does the bootstrap confidence interval represent?": "",
  "A range of plausible values for the population median, constructed from the empirical sampling distribution": "",
  "The exact range of all marathon times": "",
  "A range that only applies to these 50 specific runners": "",
  "The probability that any single runner finishes in that range": "",
  "The bootstrap confidence interval uses the distribution of medians from 10,000 resamples to create a range of plausible values for the true population median, without requiring normality assumptions.": "",
  "A quality inspector compares defect severity ratings (none, minor, major, critical) across products from three factories. Each factory contributes independent samples. The data are ordinal. Which test is appropriate?": "",
  "Three independent groups with ordinal data (severity ratings) require a nonparametric test for comparing multiple groups. The Kruskal-Wallis test is the correct choice.": "",
  "A dataset has 12 paired observations. The Wilcoxon Signed-Rank Test yields a test statistic of W = 10 with a critical value of 14 for alpha = 0.05 (two-tailed, where W must be <= critical value to reject). What is the conclusion?": "",
  "Fail to reject H-null because W = 10 is too small": "",
  "Reject H-null because W = 10 is less than or equal to the critical value of 14": "",
  "More data are needed to draw a conclusion": "",
  "The test is invalid because the sample size is too small": "",
  "For the Wilcoxon Signed-Rank Test, smaller values of W provide evidence against H-null. Since W = 10 <= 14 (the critical value), we reject H-null at alpha = 0.05.": "",
  "A psychologist wants to test whether anxiety scores differ between a control group and a treatment group. The control group (n = 12) has scores with a severe outlier of 98 (all others range 15-45). The treatment group (n = 14) has normally distributed scores ranging 10-35. Which test should she use and why?": "",
  "ANOVA because there are two groups": "",
  "Mann-Whitney U Test because the outlier in the control group would distort the t-test but has minimal impact on a rank-based test": "",
  "Paired t-test because the groups are being compared": "",
  "Independent t-test because both groups have more than 10 observations": "",
  "The extreme outlier (98) would inflate the control group mean and standard deviation, distorting a t-test. The Mann-Whitney U Test uses ranks, so the outlier simply receives the highest rank without disproportionately affecting the result.": ""
